body_html:
@Exuro889 : Please include all information asked for in the new issue template. Without that, it is hard to be able to help. For example, what do you mean by the "latest version of TensorFlow"? (Built from source? Or the latest release version?) What was the full code snippet you used (what is inception_v2_arg_scope() for example)?

Anyway, I think I was able to reduce this to the following with TensorFlow 1.0.1:

git clone https://github.com/tensorflow/models.git
cd ./models/slim

Then in Python

import tensorflow as tf
from nets import inception_v2

scaled_input_tensor = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, shape=[1, 299, 299, 3])
logits, end_points = inception_v2.inception_v2(scaled_input_tensor, is_training=False)

yields the error:

ValueError: Can not squeeze dim[1], expected a dimension of 1, got 2 for 'InceptionV2/Logits/SpatialSqueeze' (op: 'Squeeze') with input shapes: [1,2,2,1000].

@sguada @nathansilberman : Mind taking a look?

body:
@Exuro889 : Please include all information asked for in the new issue template. Without that, it is hard to be able to help. For example, what do you mean by the "latest version of TensorFlow"? (Built from source? Or the latest release version?) What was the full code snippet you used (what is `inception_v2_arg_scope()` for example)?

Anyway, I think I was able to reduce this to the following with TensorFlow 1.0.1:

```sh
git clone https://github.com/tensorflow/models.git
cd ./models/slim
```

Then in Python

```python
import tensorflow as tf
from nets import inception_v2

scaled_input_tensor = tf.placeholder(tf.float32, shape=[1, 299, 299, 3])
logits, end_points = inception_v2.inception_v2(scaled_input_tensor, is_training=False)
```

yields the error:

```
ValueError: Can not squeeze dim[1], expected a dimension of 1, got 2 for 'InceptionV2/Logits/SpatialSqueeze' (op: 'Squeeze') with input shapes: [1,2,2,1000].
```

@sguada @nathansilberman : Mind taking a look?
